missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:38:- The candidate architectures named here are broad labels, not audited frameworks. "Critical-element rigidity," "tensor stretching control," and "Lagrangian persistence" each hide many incompatible subproblems. A candidate can look attached while still floating above the real bottleneck.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:39:- "Name the exact bottleneck term or theorem gap" is the right demand, but the chain does not require any quantitative target. Changing a bottleneck how much? By derivative count, exponent, cancellation, coercivity, compactness, or propagation time? Without a gain metric, attachment can still be cosmetic.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:50:- "Supposed gain is only cosmetic" is again a vulnerable phrase. Cosmetic relative to what closure scheme? A gain that is cosmetic for De Giorgi may be decisive for concentration-compactness or Lagrangian persistence. Because the chain spans multiple architectures, the anti-cosmetic test needs architecture-specific criteria, not one global slogan.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/attacks/chain-01.md:74:The chain claims to rank mechanisms spanning critical elements, tensor routes, Lagrangian routes, and possibly stochastic structures. Those routes have different currencies of progress: compactness, coercivity, localization stability, propagation, or dynamical rigidity. Without a common scoring rubric, "ranking" is largely evaluator preference disguised as output discipline.
