missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-03.md:5:The exact local tensor relations among strain `S`, pressure Hessian `\nabla^2 p`, and vorticity stretching may carry NS-specific rigidity that scalar norm estimates erase. The point is not to get a better pressure norm, but to see whether eigenvalue, eigenvector, sign, or local harmonic-Hessian information can control the full stretching mechanism.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-03.md:16:This chain is tensorial rather than compactness-based or Lagrangian. It reuses pressure-side information, but not through the already-killed coefficient-shrinkage route.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/planner.md:32:Central premise: if blowup exists, the right object may be a minimal blowup profile, not a sharper local estimate. This chain asks whether the existing NS profile-decomposition machinery is strong enough to isolate a critical element and whether any NS-specific rigidity mechanism survives Tao's filter.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/planner.md:38:Central premise: the exact tensor identities linking strain, pressure Hessian, and vorticity stretching may contain NS-specific rigidity that averaged quadratic models do not retain. The target is a conditional criterion or obstruction phrased in eigenframe dynamics rather than scalar norms.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/planner.md:48:- Chain 05 is tensorial. It focuses on pointwise identities, eigenframes, and strain-pressure coupling rather than tube geometry or compactness.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/final-decider.md:10:- from Chain 03: an explicit prior-art and Tao-sensitivity screen for any promoted rigidity quantity, treated as a secondary discriminator rather than the main gate.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/final-decider.md:16:First, it has the strongest novelty ceiling. If it works positively at all, it does not merely rank obstructions or repackage tensor structure; it produces a theorem-like compactness-rigidity program with one host space, one critical object, one contradiction mechanism, and one sharply identified missing lemma. That is the highest-upside presentable output in the field.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/final-decider.md:18:Second, its floor is still strong after refinement. The branch now forces an extraction-package audit before any rigidity rhetoric, defines the critical element before choosing a rigidity mechanism, and allows a precise obstruction result if the route dies at extraction, formulation, definability, coercivity, or contradiction. That makes failure informative rather than aesthetic.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/final-decider.md:38:- any promoted rigidity quantity in Chain 02 should face an explicit prior-art check;
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/final-decider.md:43:Execute **Chain 02** as the mission's canonical next chain, with the imported refinements listed above and no further broadening. The output standard remains theorem-like: either a conditional compactness-rigidity program in one audited host space, or a precise obstruction map locating the first fatal break.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:5:If all local estimate cleanups are exhausted, the remaining path may be to assume blowup, extract a minimal counterexample in a critical phase space, and rule it out using a rigidity mechanism that depends on exact NS structure unavailable to Tao's averaged model.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:11:- a concrete critical-element program with one named phase space, one named rigidity lever, and one explicit first missing lemma; or
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:12:- an obstruction map showing exactly why compactness extraction or NS-specific rigidity still fails.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:16:This is the only chain that starts from a hypothetical singular solution and tries to win globally through concentration-compactness and rigidity rather than through a new local estimate.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:20:### Step 1 - Choose the phase space before discussing rigidity
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:23:- Action: rank realistic critical or near-critical spaces such as `L^3`, `\dot H^{1/2}`, and `BMO^{-1}` by extraction feasibility, known theorem support, and compatibility with a suitable weak or mild-solution framework.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:25:- Kill condition: if no candidate space supports a credible minimal-element package, stop and record a compactness-floor obstruction.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:27:### Step 2 - Fix one candidate rigidity lever up front
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:30:- Action: choose one exact NS structure that could exclude the critical element, such as a tensor-sign law, Lagrangian/topological invariant, or a pressure-Hessian feature.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:32:- Expected output: a rigidity-screen memo naming one promoted lever and one backup.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:33:- Kill condition: if no Tao-sensitive rigidity lever can be named before the extraction package is built, terminate the branch negatively.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:38:- Action: formulate the hypothetical minimal blowup object, record the symmetry normalization, and state exactly what compactness or almost-periodicity statements are required.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:42:### Step 4 - Stress-test the rigidity route on the dossier
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:45:- Action: run the promoted rigidity lever against the hypothetical critical element and identify the exact contradiction pathway.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:54:- Expected output: either a compactness-plus-rigidity roadmap or a calibrated negative memo with precise failure points.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-004/planner-chains/chain-02.md:55:- Kill condition: if the final claim blurs multiple phase spaces or multiple rigidity levers that were not actually audited, narrow it.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/selector.md:25:   The best geometry-first candidate. It targets NS-specific vortex structure rather than norms or compactness machinery, and its negative outcomes remain useful because they cleanly separate local geometric depletion from global alignment fantasy.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/selector.md:31:   Highest proof ceiling, but the weakest floor for adversarial testing in this run. It is the most likely to die at the supercritical compactness gate before exposing a comparably concrete NS-specific structural property, so it is better kept as a later escalation path than as one of the first three tests.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:47:This step is necessary, but it is under-specified at the exact point where the chain needs rigidity.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-01.md:93:- The chain assumes that the main valuable positive output would be a closure criterion or theorem target. A sharp obstruction, rigidity statement, or clean no-go theorem for a reformulation family could be more realistic and more valuable.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-001/selected/chain-02.md:16:This is the only chain whose core question is "can the nonlinear interaction itself be reformulated into a better mechanism?" It is not a localization chain, not a geometry chain, and not a compactness chain.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:5:The file `selected/chain-03.md` is titled "Chain 04." That is minor administratively, but it is also a planning smell: the chain is being treated as a distinct route while its identity is already blurred at the labeling level. For a compactness-and-rigidity program, sloppiness about which route is being evaluated is not harmless. It increases the chance that later conclusions quietly pool evidence from neighboring chains.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:9:### Step 1 - Choose a critical phase space and pre-screen for rigidity
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:15:- The candidate list (`L^3`, `dot H^{1/2}`, `BMO^{-1}`) mixes spaces with very different compactness, stability, and uniqueness behavior, but the step acts as if "extraction feasibility" is a comparable scalar score. It is not. A space can be good for mild-solution local theory and still be bad for the kind of precompactness modulo symmetry that a critical-element scheme needs.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:16:- The requirement that each candidate come with "one plausible rigidity lever" front-loads the hardest unsolved part. That is not a screening criterion; it is almost the whole problem. In Navier-Stokes, extraction and rigidity are not separable checkboxes.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:17:- `BMO^{-1}` is especially suspect here. It is natural for small-data theory, but as a habitat for a minimal blowup object it is weak, nonlocal, and poorly matched to the kind of pointwise or geometric rigidity mechanisms later advertised.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:18:- `L^3` and `dot H^{1/2}` are more realistic, but the chain does not state what notion of solution is being minimized over, what continuation criterion defines the threshold, or what stability theory is assumed. Without that, "rank realistic candidate spaces" is premature.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:19:- The kill condition is calibrated too aggressively. "No plausible NS-specific rigidity handle" is likely true at the start, but that does not mean the route is worthless. It may still yield a sharp obstruction map. The chain claims to allow that outcome later, yet Step 1 would terminate before any serious obstruction analysis is done.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:27:This is the standard move imported from dispersive concentration-compactness, but here the chain understates how much nontrivial machinery is being assumed.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:31:- "Formulate the hypothetical minimal blowup object" makes it sound as if the object is available once a space is chosen. In reality, this step may already require a profile decomposition, nonlinear perturbation theory, stability under the chosen topology, and a sharp threshold definition compatible with Navier-Stokes scaling.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:32:- The phrase "normalize symmetries" hides a genuine issue: the symmetry group for Navier-Stokes is not just a technical nuisance. Translation and scaling are manageable in principle, but the pressure and nonlocal interactions make compactness modulo symmetry materially harder than in many semilinear dispersive models.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:34:- The distinction between "already available in the literature" and "missing" is necessary, but the chain does not force precision about theorem hypotheses. A result proved for mild solutions in one class and a rigidity argument stated for suitable weak solutions in another class do not combine automatically.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:35:- The kill condition is underpowered. "Cannot be formulated cleanly" is too weak a standard. A minimal element can often be formulated in a paper sense while still lacking the compactness or regularity features needed for any contradiction argument. This step needs to reject pseudo-formulations, not merely ill-posed ones.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:41:### Step 3 - Stress-test one rigidity route against Tao's barrier
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:48:- The route list is too heterogeneous. Backward uniqueness, Liouville theorems, self-similar rigidity, and geometric concentration laws operate at different regularity levels and require different solution notions. Lumping them together invites false comparisons.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:49:- The instruction to test whether a route uses "exact NS structure rather than only compactness plus harmonic analysis" is right in spirit but vague in practice. Many arguments use the NS equation explicitly while still providing no genuine leverage beyond Tao-preserved structure. The chain needs a sharper criterion than rhetorical NS-specificity.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:50:- Tao's barrier is treated as a binary filter, but the relevant question is quantitative: does the rigidity route exploit a monotone quantity, sign structure, epsilon-regularity mechanism, or unique continuation input that survives the scaling and compactness regime of the minimal element? Without that refinement, the memo may only restate "this still looks too harmonic-analytic."
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:51:- The kill condition is again too compressed. A route can fail for reasons other than collapsing to Tao-preserved structure: wrong solution class, no time directionality, non-closedness under limits, incompatibility with almost-periodic scaling, or the need for extra decay that a critical element will not have.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:57:### Step 4 - Organize any surviving rigidity route into a contradiction program
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:63:- The step assumes "one rigidity route survives" is a meaningful event. In practice, many routes survive only as slogans. Turning them into a contradiction program usually reveals that the surviving route needs a compactness property, decay estimate, or exclusion theorem equivalent in difficulty to the original problem.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:64:- "Keep the dependence on the chosen phase space explicit" is necessary, but it is not enough. The contradiction path also depends on the solution class, normalization, time interval geometry, and what compactness topology is available. The chain is still underspecified.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:80:- There is no explicit instruction to compare the final claim against known concentration-compactness and rigidity programs in Navier-Stokes or adjacent critical PDE. Without that, the chain risks rediscovering a familiar dead end and calling it a new obstruction map.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:90:The supposed sequence is not really sequential. Step 1 already demands a plausible NS-specific rigidity lever, which is exactly the scarce resource the rest of the chain is supposed to uncover or disprove. Later steps mostly elaborate that same question in different language.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:94:That template is powerful, but here it may be more a framing trap than a guide. The chain assumes that if local mechanism hunts fail, the right global object is a minimal blowup profile. That is a substantive bet, not a neutral fallback. Navier-Stokes may resist this style of attack precisely because the available rigidity inputs are too weak or too noncritical to close the loop.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:96:### 3. "NS-specific rigidity" is never operationalized tightly enough
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:98:This is the biggest methodological gap. Exact use of the Navier-Stokes equation is not the same as genuine new leverage. Without a concrete criterion such as a non-generic monotonicity, coercive sign structure, limit-stable geometric invariant, or unique continuation mechanism compatible with the critical compactness class, the chain can mistake formal equation dependence for actual progress.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:106:This matters throughout. Mild solutions in critical spaces, suitable weak solutions, local energy solutions, and ancient/self-similar limits each support different tools. A compactness argument that crosses these regimes without explicit compatibility checks is fragile.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:110:A compactness-plus-rigidity route for critical Navier-Stokes has obvious prior-art adjacency. Without an explicit prior-art comparison checkpoint, the chain risks spending several steps to conclude something already broadly understood: extraction can be imagined, but no rigidity input closes the contradiction at critical scaling.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:124:- It treats "find a plausible rigidity handle" as though it were a screening detail rather than the core unsolved obstacle.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:125:- It imports a concentration-compactness template without first justifying that Navier-Stokes has the right rigidity ecology for that template to be more than aspirational.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/attacks/chain-03.md:128:If this chain is kept, it should be judged almost entirely by the quality of its obstruction map. A positive program should only be credited if it identifies a rigidity mechanism that is not merely Navier-Stokes-flavored in wording, but demonstrably limit-stable, phase-space-compatible, and stronger than the generic structures Tao's barrier already preserves.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/selector.md:9:   Best high-upside and most globally different chain. It is the clean alternative if local mechanism hunts stall, and even a negative result produces a reusable compactness-and-rigidity obstruction map.
missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-003/selector.md:32:- **Chain 04** preserves the necessary high-upside gamble. It is the only route here that starts from a hypothetical blowup object and looks for an NS-specific rigidity mechanism.
